  # How to Format Blog Posts: 7 Tips to Boost Engagement
  
  Author: [Tan Siew Ann](https://www.semrush.com/blog/user/siew-ann-tan/)
  
  10 min read
  
  June 26, 2024
  
  Contributors: [Rachel Handley](https://www.semrush.com/blog/user/203873905/) and [Bartłomiej Barcik](https://www.semrush.com/blog/user/207807681/)
  
  Table of contents
  
  Creating a high-quality blog post isn’t as simple as writing all the proper words.
  
  The way it’s formatted also makes a huge difference.
  
  But before we get into formatting details, let’s start with the basics.
  
  ## What Is a Blog Post Format?
  
  A blog post format refers to the way you present your blog post’s ideas.
  
  It covers elements like:
  
  - **How you present concepts**. In text, image, or video form, for example.
  - **How you display key points**. To emphasize their importance.
  - **The content’s structure**. Which determines whether your blog post is easy to navigate and digest.
  
  For example, the blog post below:
  
  - Has a subheading that describes the subtopic
  - Uses a numbered list for step-by-step instructions that are easy to follow
  - Bolds words that users need to click when following the post’s instructions
  - Provides an image to support an instruction
  
  ![Semrush instructional blog post format with subheading, numbered list, bold text, and image.](https://static.semrush.com/blog/uploads/media/7e/57/7e57355446935b7b80058519f3bbe317/147b00b8c3fd234c58763b5268399f63/google-lens.png)
  
  ## Why Does Blog Post Formatting Matter?
  
  The format of a blog post affects:
  
  - **Whether the blog post is easy to skim**. People often scan posts to see if it satisfies their needs. And good blog post formatting can make this easier.
  - **The amount of time users spend engaging with the post**. Effectively formatted posts are simpler to digest, holding readers’ attention for longer.
  - **The blog post’s ability to communicate concepts**. Formatting certain blog ideas in image or chart form, for example, can help readers understand them better.
  
  All this influences the blog post’s potential for generating conversions (i.e., desirable actions like account registrations).
  
  For example, compare these two variations of the same text:
  
  ![Two versions of similar blog post text. One is an unformatted chunk of text and the other is well formatted.](https://static.semrush.com/blog/uploads/media/eb/dd/ebdd56ee9f67f43e5e8d9a6b917ed609/50f57f6d9481db8e2b1d9d38fce8636d/AD_4nXf_GP1mXMKtuegkBnB0qV5XsvvgPLJG8Q-z4I2Z_ABznOPCloyPecfVEsAX0-cKX1NhpAcvPeL1QwFJgaPHvbpW9GqAWgPD2vmwqEoGOdRWAf0n3zDYzZnY8rcxWrOB8q94g750-Xx6WCzmIdPiRXpzgvuV.png)
  
  The version on the left is an unformatted chunk of text that seems daunting and off-putting to read. Its [call to action](https://www.semrush.com/blog/what-is-a-call-to-action/) (CTA) also doesn’t stand out, which could harm its conversion rate.
  
  Meanwhile, the version on the right is well-formatted with a heading, line breaks, a bulleted list, and a CTA banner. It’s easier to read and could attract more conversions.
  
  ## How to Format a Blog Post
  
  Here’s how to format a blog post to improve engagement and conversions:
  
  ### 1\. Use Headings to Indicate Key Discussion Points
  
  Use headings to break your content into sections. To summarize the content’s main idea, helping readers understand what they’ll learn from reading it.
  
  For example, “1. Use Headings to Indicate Key Discussion Points” is this content section’s heading. And clearly spells out what will be discussed.
  
  Readers can also skim a blog post’s headings. To get the gist of its content without reading it in full.
  
  #### Adding Heading Tags to Your Headings
  
  Add hypertext markup language (HTML) [heading tags](https://www.semrush.com/blog/header-tag/) to differentiate the post’s headings from regular text. Which helps search engines understand your content’s structure and helps readers identify headings and their hierarchy.
  
  The heading tags go before and after the intended heading. Like so:
  
  `<hX>The heading goes here</hX>`
  
  “X” is a number from one to six, depending on the heading’s hierarchy within the post:
  
  - The H1 heading should represent the post’s title
  - H2 headings signal the start of a main content section
  - H3 headings indicate subtopics within a main content section
  
  And so on.
  
  ![A diagram of 6 headings with heading tags ranging from H1 to H6. The H2 heading is a subheading of the H1 heading, the H3 heading is a subheading of the H2 heading, and so on.](https://static.semrush.com/blog/uploads/media/c2/82/c282c83faa1ef841988066260efc1353/ed22808a0311c2e55c2b1e4917b417b7/AD_4nXdmtjAc75_o4QjQWOcXQOJ2XzYgNMNdXVmg3BYQ6LDuxLl7oithWW4-amoc5CBV_HzzuylWOwYE5IL-H2mPrkH_1TZDW_P4DLUpLW0BlPvURKVLpKBbWzpWe-s_QoQi2Y3gL-GQXhUcQONQAI8xyfVABQAY.png)
  
  Most writing apps and content management systems (CMSs) make it easy to create heading tags.
  
  For example, here’s what an H2 looks like in Google Docs:
  
  ![H2 heading and heading format setting highlighted in Google docs editor.](https://static.semrush.com/blog/uploads/media/a1/5c/a15c51d5cfdd99b51ec80cbc05d132a5/45ab30445eef06015d02473576aededf/AD_4nXcmozqoB4KuScOb7mC06Po968A6lDVt-1AWesObgPMUEDeb-4tUuU9f53--z0gSVbJdV0O1YG4oMaT7_7thvtdjhO6yXAaZqJXVGxQLICErDHCaaETfSe8SchZFL096oIo8MaFLicoPcOpSnV62b_RCUe8.png)
  
  And in WordPress:
  
  ![h2 heading text and h2 in toolbar highlighted in WordPress editor.](https://static.semrush.com/blog/uploads/media/17/8a/178ae4e5be59a05461b86deec21e75a3/7d4ab3b67949e686b1c73b04843c751a/AD_4nXcaA__2OszItN6fM1ARHyA58EfcTvDpG1Y31cfF0cls1McaN_ibWyi7xHwYA-rLd7Nx_O-4VSXvyOWCfWzRDTz4GZzIjik1lBYFgYSfywSNyPjGFQ20VmFE8k0a5g7RiXvyFC2qa0KdVXCzQFX-DwAenr03.png)
  
  This means you don’t need to apply the HTML tags manually.
  
  #### Creating a Table of Contents with Your Headings
  
  A table of contents is a list of your post’s headings. It helps readers view all these headings at a glance. And decide whether your post contains the information they’re looking for.
  
  For example, here’s the table of contents for our mobile advertising blog post:
  
  ![Table of contents highlighted in sidebar of Semrush blog post.](https://static.semrush.com/blog/uploads/media/e3/b7/e3b734362882f21c55d03180d2cc7eb7/957580e918c928af35584c1661047de8/AD_4nXcyUlgNQawgXBA-wGrplU9RE8sRD-Xyu5fqN42lBfV-Dtb9H86lfnixknz0-3h74dZma3zUBnrvxWFP1VwenVaNkGgJq4jpOSTswq17zKg4hFmXPxkPP1iQL-qjcKB3Yeykux7DL_MCXoYS8bS7nra4qOM6.png)
  
  Each heading in the table of contents may also be a [jump link](https://www.semrush.com/blog/ahref-link/#anchor-links). Letting people who click it skip directly to its content section.
  
  If you’re creating a WordPress post, you can use the [Easy Table of Contents](https://wordpress.org/plugins/easy-table-of-contents/) plugin to add tables of contents to your posts.
  
